Solution — Exercise 05: Valgrind Use-After-Free
=================================================

Step 1: Run with Valgrind
  valgrind --leak-check=full ./target

Step 2: Read the report
  Invalid read of size 4
    at main (target.c:27)       ← printf("Value after free: %d\n", node->value)
    Address is 0 bytes inside a block of size 48 free'd
    at free (vg_replace_malloc.c:...)
    by main (target.c:24)       ← free(node)

  Invalid write of size 4
    at main (target.c:28)       ← node->value = 99
    Address is 0 bytes inside a block of size 48 free'd

Answers:
  - Error type: "Invalid read" / "Invalid write" (use-after-free)
  - Lines: 27 (read) and 28 (write), after free() on line 24
  - Why silent: freed memory isn't zeroed — old data remains readable
    until the allocator reuses the block for something else

Why it matters:
  Use-after-free is one of the most exploited bug classes.
  An attacker can arrange for a controlled allocation to fill
  the freed slot — turning a dangling pointer into a code
  execution primitive. CVEs built on this class include
  major browser, kernel, and OS vulnerabilities.

Step 3: Read the flag with GDB
  The flag is stored in node->label. Even after free(), the memory
  is not zeroed — the string remains readable.
  gdb ./target
  (gdb) break main
  (gdb) run
  (gdb) next    (step past strcpy)
  (gdb) print node->label
  → $1 = "HRZ{dangling_ptr}"

  Submit it: horizon done HRZ{dangling_ptr}
